    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and trace.csv (use full available series). Provide compact summaries: \n1) List unique cmdb_id values found in each file. \n2) For metric.csv: list unique kpi_name values and total row count. Then for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: count, mean, p50 (median), p95, min, max. Return up to top 50 rows ordered by count desc. \n3) For trace.csv: list unique trace_name values and total row count. Then for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute: count, mean, p50, p95, min, max. Return up to top 50 rows ordered by count desc. \nEnsure P95 is computed on the full series (no time filtering). Keep outputs compact (only requested aggregates and top rows)." 
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step loaded metric.csv and trace.csv and produced global aggregation summaries (per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and per (cmdb_id, trace_name)) including counts, means, medians and P95 values computed on the full available series. We now have visibility of the candidate components (many os_*, docker_*, db_*) and the set of KPI and trace names. These global aggregates satisfy the requirement to compute thresholds on the full series before any time-range filtering. None of the incident-window-specific anomaly detection was performed yet. Next we must (1) compute full-series thresholds (P95 and P05) for each component-KPI / component-trace, (2) filter the raw time series to the incident window (May 27, 2020 05:00 to 05:30 in UTC+8), and (3) identify anomalies inside that window by comparing values to the precomputed thresholds (both high-side spikes value >= P95 and low-side drops value <= P05). From those anomalies we should produce compact aggregates (counts and earliest anomaly timestamp per group) to find candidate faulty components and times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the existing metric.csv and trace.csv full-series data, do the following (compute thresholds BEFORE time filtering):\n1) For metric.csv: for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global P95 and P05 on the full available series and keep them in a table (store in kernel). Then filter metric.csv rows to the incident window May 27, 2020 05:00 to 05:30 (UTC+8). Join the filtered rows with their group's P95/P05 and mark a row as an anomaly if value >= P95 or value <= P05. Aggregate anomalies by (cmdb_id, kpi_name): provide count of anomaly points and the earliest anomaly timestamp per group. Return the top 20 groups ordered by anomaly count desc, and also return the total number of metric anomalies found in the window.\n2) For trace.csv: similarly compute global P95 and P05 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) from the full series. Then filter trace.csv rows to the same incident window, join thresholds, mark anomalies where value >= P95 or value <= P05, and aggregate by (cmdb_id, trace_name) to produce count and earliest anomaly timestamp. Return the top 20 trace groups ordered by anomaly count desc, and the total number of trace anomalies found in the window.\n3) Keep outputs compact: for each returned row include cmdb_id, kpi_name (or trace_name), anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, threshold_p95, threshold_p05, and sample (min/max) values within window if useful. Limit rows to top 20 for metrics and top 20 for traces. Do not print full raw time series." 
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps computed global thresholds and detected many metric anomalies in the incident window. The top metric anomaly groups are dominated by redis nodes and show continuous 30-minute anomaly runs, but their severity_score is 0.0 because window values equal the computed P95/P05 (likely measurement artifact or sustained constant values). Because metric severity is zero for these top groups, they are unlikely to be the true root cause. According to the diagnosis workflow, we should next analyze traces to (1) find container/service-level faults that show real deviations from their thresholds, and (2) use trace timing and downstream position to localize the root cause component. We need compact fault-identification aggregates for trace groups (consecutive segments, run lengths, and severity) to rank candidates. This will narrow candidates to trace groups with actual breach magnitude > 0 and with earliest occurrence within the incident window.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the trace anomalies table previously computed (full-series thresholds were applied and anomalies inside 2020-05-27 05:00–05:30 UTC+8 were flagged), perform fault-identification on the top 20 trace groups by anomaly_count: for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute compact fields using only rows inside the incident window: total_anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, number_of_consecutive_anomaly_segments (count of disjoint consecutive-minute anomaly runs), longest_consecutive_run_length (minutes), window_min, window_max, p95, p05, and severity_score. Define severity_score as: if high-side anomaly (window_max >= p95) use (window_max - p95) / (p95 + 1e-12); if low-side anomaly (window_min <= p05) use (p05 - window_min) / (abs(p05) + 1e-12); if both apply use the larger. Return up to 20 rows with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, total_anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, number_of_consecutive_anomaly_segments, longest_consecutive_run_length, window_min, window_max, p95, p05, severity_score. Order rows by severity_score desc then total_anomaly_count desc. Keep output compact (top 20 rows only)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global thresholds and detected anomalies in the incident window. Metric anomalies are dominated by redis nodes but show zero severity (window values equal global thresholds) and thus are unlikely to be the true root cause. Trace-level fault identification highlighted one clear high-side breach: docker_003 | trace.self.jdbc.duration_p95 with severity_score = 2.0 and earliest_anomaly_ts = 2020-05-27 05:00:00 CST (UTC+8). This single non-zero-severity trace fault is the leading candidate for the root cause component and occurrence time, but the underlying reason (e.g., DB connection limit/close, CPU, or network) is not yet determined. To decide the root cause reason we must inspect docker_003's traces in the incident window to see which trace types breached thresholds and fetch related metrics (e.g., container CPU, DB-related metrics) to distinguish DB-side vs node-side vs network issues.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the incident window (May 27, 2020 05:00 to 05:30, UTC+8) inspect trace.csv restricted to cmdb_id == 'docker_003'. Provide two compact outputs: \n1) Aggregated summary by trace_name: for each trace_name compute count, earliest timestamp, window_min, window_max, mean. Return up to top 20 rows ordered by count desc. \n2) Raw rows (ordered by timestamp asc) for trace_name == 'trace.self.jdbc.duration_p95' limited to top 50 rows, showing columns timestamp, trace_name, value. \nKeep outputs compact (only requested aggregates and up to 50 detail rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have identified a focused trace-level anomaly: docker_003 | trace.self.jdbc.duration_p95 shows a clear high-side breach (severity_score = 2.0). In the incident window (2020-05-27 05:00–05:30 UTC+8) docker_003 traces are sampled each minute (30 samples). The JDBC p95 series is normally ~0.003 with a few higher values (0.004) and one notable spike to 0.012. Top metric anomalies (redis nodes) show constant values equal to thresholds and zero breach severity, so they are likely instrumentation/constant-state rather than the single failure. To localize the root cause reason we must now check related metrics on docker_003 and on DB services (db_*) for evidence of DB-side issues (connection limit/close), node resource problems (CPU), or network problems. Specifically, we need compact metric-anomaly evidence for docker_003 and all db_* components in the incident window: counts, earliest timestamps, window min/max, thresholds and breach severity. This will let us see whether DB metrics show high rejected connections, connection drops, or resource saturation coinciding with docker_003 JDBC p95 spike.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the previously computed metric-anomaly results for the incident window (use metric_anom/metric_anom_top or recompute if needed), filter to components where cmdb_id == 'docker_003' OR cmdb_id starts with 'db_'. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, window_min, window_max, p95, p05, and severity_score (same formula used earlier: high-side (window_max>=p95) -> (window_max-p95)/(p95+1e-12); low-side (window_min<=p05) -> (p05-window_min)/(abs(p05)+1e-12); take the larger if both apply). Also compute per-component total_anomalies (sum of anomaly_count by cmdb_id). Return two compact tables: \n1) Per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) rows with columns [cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, window_min, window_max, p95, p05, severity_score], limited to rows with severity_score > 0, ordered by severity_score desc then anomaly_count desc, top 20 rows. \n2) Per-component summary table with columns [cmdb_id, total_anomalies], ordered by total_anomalies desc (include all db_* and docker_003 rows). Keep outputs compact (top20 for table 1; all components for table 2)."
}

